value.name: Cassiopeia (constellation) - Wikipedia
value.snippet: Cassiopeia(listen) is a constellationin the northern sky named after the vain queen Cassiopeia, mother of Andromeda, in Greek mythology, who boasted about her unrivaled beauty. Cassiopeia was one of the 48 constellations listed by the 2nd-century Greek astronomer Ptolemy, and it remains one of the 88 modern constellations today.

value.name: 4 Cassiopeiae – Wikipedia
value.snippet: 4 Cassiopeiae, som är stjärnans Flamsteed-beteckning, är en gles dubbelstjärna i den mellersta delen av stjärnbilden Cassiopeja. Den har en genomsnittlig skenbar magnitud på ca 4,96 och är synlig för blotta ögat där ljusföroreningar ej förekommer. Baserat på parallaxmätning inom Hipparcosuppdraget på ca 4,2 mas, beräknas den befinna sig på ett avstånd på ca 790 ljusår från solen. Den rör sig närmare solen med en heliocentrisk radiell hastighet på ca -39 km/s. På det ...

value.name: Cassiopeia - Se, hvordan du finder stjernebilledet her | illvid.dk
value.snippet: Stjernebilledet Cassiopeia er et stjernebillede på den nordlige halvkugle, hvor det kan ses året rundt. Cassiopeia kan også i nogle perioder ses fra den nordligste del af den sydlige halvkugle. Det bedste tidspunkt at se Cassiopeia fra den sydlige halvkugle er fra november til december.

value.name: Cassiopeia Constellation | Facts, Information, History & Definition
value.snippet: Theta Cassiopeiae, also known as Marfak, is an A-type main-sequence star with an apparent magnitude of 4.3. Marfak is located at around 134 light-years away from us. This star is 1.8 times more massive than our Sun, having 2.6 times its radius, and it is also considerably hotter, having average surface temperatures of around 8,202 K. 6 Cassiopeiae

value.name: A guide to the constellation - BBC Sky at Night Magazine
value.snippet: Cassiopeia was the wife of King Cepheus and mother to Princess Andromeda. Cassiopeia was sent into the sky as punishment for boasting that she and Andromeda were more beautiful than the Nereids, who were sea nymphs. From the UK, the W-shaped constellation of Cassiopeia appears circumpolar, meaning it never sets.

value.snippet: These names have been passed from ancient civilizations and they are usually of Greek or Arabic origin. Designation: Abbreviation of the scientific name or designation if it doesn’t have one.
